# Copy to .env for LOCAL DEV ONLY. Do NOT commit .env, and do NOT put real
# production secrets in a local .env — production secrets belong ONLY in the Vercel
# project's Environment Variables (Settings > Environment Variables). The local .env
# is git-ignored, but keeping prod creds out of the working tree entirely is safest.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# DATABASE_URL — MySQL / MariaDB connection.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Deployment: the app runs on Vercel and connects to your cPanel MySQL over the
# internet (cPanel > Remote MySQL must allow the connecting host). Use the cPanel
# SERVER's IP/hostname (cPanel home > "Shared IP Address"), NOT your website domain
# — the domain points to Vercel. cPanel prefixes DB and user names with your
# account, e.g. acct_yardflow and acct_yfuser.
#
# IMPORTANT — set these query params:
#   • connection_limit=1  → on serverless (Vercel) each warm instance should hold at
#     most ONE direct connection, or a traffic burst across many instances will
#     exhaust shared hosting's low per-user cap (often 10–30) and every request 500s.
#     For a pooler / Prisma Accelerate you can raise this.
#   • sslaccept=strict    → REQUIRE TLS so credentials and query results don't cross
#     the public internet in clear text. If your host uses a self-signed cert and
#     strict fails, fall back to sslaccept=accept_invalid_certs (still encrypted),
#     but prefer a valid cert.
#
#   mysql://acct_yfuser:THE_PASSWORD@CPANEL_SERVER_IP:3306/acct_yardflow?connection_limit=1&sslaccept=strict
#
# Local dev against a local MySQL, if you ever want one (TLS optional locally):
#   mysql://root:yourpassword@localhost:3306/yardflow?connection_limit=5
DATABASE_URL="mysql://USER:PASSWORD@CPANEL_SERVER_IP:3306/DBNAME?connection_limit=1&sslaccept=strict"

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SESSION_SECRET — signs the auth session cookie (HMAC). REQUIRED in production.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Generate a long random value, e.g.:  openssl rand -base64 48
# If unset off-Vercel, a well-known insecure dev fallback is used (fine for local
# only). Never ship the fallback to production — set this in Vercel env vars.
SESSION_SECRET="generate-a-long-random-value"
